docs.abstract: After three years and more than 130 columns, the smartphone was tops. There were also some deliberate Luddites among us.
docs.snippet: After three years and more than 130 columns, the smartphone was tops. There were also some deliberate Luddites among us.
docs.lead_paragraph: Several years ago, some colleagues and I were chatting about what was missing from tech journalism. Plenty of news media outlets had written breathlessly about hot new gadgets and apps. But what were people really doing with that tech?

headline.main: What We Learned About the Technology That Times Journalists Use
headline.print_headline: The Technology We Use and Why It Matters

docs.abstract: A decentralized internet was hailed as a way to dethrone Twitter and Facebook. But to the tech giants, the idea could unload some of their burdens.
docs.snippet: A decentralized internet was hailed as a way to dethrone Twitter and Facebook. But to the tech giants, the idea could unload some of their burdens.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Not so long ago, the technology behind Bitcoin was seen in Silicon Valley as the best hope for challenging the enormous, centralized power of companies like Twitter and Facebook.

headline.main: Twitter and Facebook Want to Shift Power to Users. Or Do They?
headline.print_headline: Will Big Tech Shift Power To Its Users?

docs.abstract: Andrew Bailey, the head of a financial regulator, will take over the role from Mark Carney.
docs.snippet: Andrew Bailey, the head of a financial regulator, will take over the role from Mark Carney.
docs.lead_paragraph: The British government on Friday named Andrew Bailey, the head of the Financial Conduct Authority, to be the next chief of the Bank of England. Mr. Bailey, who worked at the central bank for over 30 years before leaving to run the financial watchdog in 2016, will succeed Mark Carney.

headline.main: Bank of England Picks New Governor to Guide It After Brexit
headline.print_headline: Bank of England Selects Post-Brexit Leader

docs.abstract: The private Concours Club in Miami aims to create a golf club feeling for car enthusiasts. Tracks like it are scattered across the U.S., but they aren’t cheap.

docs.lead_paragraph: As his days throttling IndyCars up to 240 miles an hour begin to wind down, Helio Castroneves is looking forward to kicking back at a country club.

headline.main: Country Clubs Where Drives Can Hit 150 M.P.H.
headline.print_headline: Country Clubs Where Par Is 150 M.P.H.

docs.abstract: President Jair Bolsonaro of Brazil said Mr. Trump decided not to pursue tariffs on Brazilian steel after a phone call on Friday.
docs.snippet: President Jair Bolsonaro of Brazil said Mr. Trump decided not to pursue tariffs on Brazilian steel after a phone call on Friday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump has backed off a threat he made this month to impose tariffs on Brazilian metal, a move that would have broken a previous agreement with the country and risked reigniting trade tensions.

headline.main: Trump Backs Down From Threat to Place Tariffs on Brazilian Steel
headline.print_headline: Trump Lifts Threat of Tariffs on Brazilian Metal

docs.abstract: A state law meant to target Uber and Lyft has repercussions for contributors to the sports site SB Nation.
docs.snippet: A state law meant to target Uber and Lyft has repercussions for contributors to the sports site SB Nation.
docs.lead_paragraph: More than 200 bloggers in California will lose regular writing gigs because of a state law meant to improve working conditions at companies like Uber and Lyft that rely on contractors rather than employees.

headline.main: Vox Media to Cut 200 Freelancers, Citing California Gig-Worker Law
headline.print_headline: Vox to Cut 200 Bloggers, Citing Gig-Worker Law

docs.abstract: Tim Leissner, the husband of Kimora Lee Simmons, will not have to pay anything beyond the $43.7 million he agreed to surrender as part of a guilty plea.
docs.snippet: Tim Leissner, the husband of Kimora Lee Simmons, will not have to pay anything beyond the $43.7 million he agreed to surrender as part of a guilty plea.
docs.lead_paragraph: Securities regulators have barred a former partner at Goldman Sachs from working in the industry more than a year after he pleaded guilty to helping orchestrate the looting of billions of dollars from a sovereign wealth fund in Malaysia.

headline.main: Ex-Goldman Sachs Partner Barred by S.E.C. Over 1MDB Scandal

docs.abstract: Tide Pod shout-outs onscreen. Flirtatious exchanges with companies on Twitter. Netflix may not run ads, but it has become a coveted marketing platform.
docs.snippet: Tide Pod shout-outs onscreen. Flirtatious exchanges with companies on Twitter. Netflix may not run ads, but it has become a coveted marketing platform.
docs.lead_paragraph: Netflix subscribers like being able to glide through entire seasons of “Stranger Things” and “The Crown” without sitting through commercials for insurance and S.U.V.s with bows on the hood. Subscriptions, rather than advertising, drive its nearly $16 billion in annual revenue, and being commercial-free “remains a deep part of our brand proposition,” Netflix said in a statement.

headline.main: Netflix Is Ad Free, but It Isn’t Brand Free
headline.print_headline: Netflix Shuns  Commercials, But Brands? Not One Bit

docs.abstract: She claims she was sidelined after reporting that her boss, an Emmy-winning producer, texted her an inappropriate photo.
docs.snippet: She claims she was sidelined after reporting that her boss, an Emmy-winning producer, texted her an inappropriate photo.
docs.lead_paragraph: An associate producer at CBS’s signature newsmagazine program “60 Minutes” claimed she was sidelined after making a formal complaint about her boss, according to a lawsuit filed against the network Tuesday.

headline.main: A Female ‘60 Minutes’ Producer Sues CBS, Claiming Discrimination
headline.print_headline: ‘60 Minutes’ Producer Says She Was Harassed, Then Sidelined

docs.abstract: The end-of-year deal is the product of months of negotiations that fell short of both parties’ hopes.
docs.snippet: The end-of-year deal is the product of months of negotiations that fell short of both parties’ hopes.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Brewers, distillers, racehorse owners, churches with parking lots and some wind energy producers won federal tax breaks in a last-hour congressional agreement on taxes and spending that was unveiled Tuesday morning.

headline.main: Congressional Negotiators Agree to Extend Some Tax Credits and Add to Debt
headline.print_headline: Tax Breaks For Interests Fall Short For Parties
